1. Introduction¶

When it comes to online ratings and reviews, everyone benefits. They have the ability to enhance merchant credibility, improve comparison shopping rankings, and raise conversion rates. Reviews can increase customer engagement and also monitor customer service efforts. Ratings and reviews can achieve all of these and more through the power of word of mouth marketing. Yelp is one of the leading websites that has been dedicated to merchants ratings and reviews including restaurants, hair salons and makeup artists, for a long time.

The original dataset is downloaded from Yelp official website(https://www.yelp.com/dataset). In total, we get information on 174,000 business in all categories, consists of six aspects for merchants i.e business, reviews, users, check-ins and tips, in an 8.65GB json file. After observing the dataset, we decide to focus on Las Vegas restaurants because Las Vegas has highest volume of data among all cities in this dataset and Las Vegas is a diverse and exceptional city in the US. Therefore, we are looking forward to get some interesting findings about what eating in Las Vegas is like, users behavior and corresponding reviews patterns.

Questions of Interest¶

  • Q1: What is the most popular type of restaurant in Las Vegas? What is the trend of check-in time for this kind of restaurant?
    Figure out the most popular type of restaurant and check-ins trends over a duration of the time.
  • Q2: What do we know about users?
    Analyze users' yelping duration, average star of their reviews, types of restaurants they visit, the businesses they checked-in and the frequency they checked in.
  • Q3: Where are the best restaurants in Las Vegas?
    Figure out where can we find the best restaurants with rating above 3, where can we find best cuisines i.e. NightLife, Japanese food, in Las Vegas?
  • Q4: What did people say about Las Vegas restaurants?
    Analyze reviews using sentiment analysis.

Description of Data¶

In order to work together more efficiently and to easily verify our output using tableau and other tools, we convert original one json file to four seperated csv file. They are 'business.csv', 'checkin.csv', 'user.csv'and 'review.csv'.

Attributes of 'business.csv' are as follows:¶

  • business_id: ID of the business
  • name: name of the business
  • city: city of the business
  • latitude: latitude of the business
  • longitude: longitude of the business
  • stars: average rating of the business
  • review_count: number of reviews received
  • categories: multiple categories of the business

Attributes of 'checkin.csv' are as follows:¶

  • business_id: ID of the business
  • Date: The dates when checkin's were done for that place

Attributes of 'user.csv' are as follows:¶

  • user_id: ID of the user
  • name: Name of the user
  • review_count: Number of reviews given by user
  • yelping_since: The dates since user started yelping
  • useful: Count of people who found the user's review useful
  • funny: Count of people who found the user's review funny
  • cool: Count of people who found the user's review cool
  • fans: Count of people who found the user's review fans
  • elite: The elite member badge given by Yelp to the user's if they reach a certain level
  • average_stars : Average Star given by a user throughout their yelp usage

Attribues of 'review.csv' are as follows:¶

  • review_id: ID of the review
  • user_id: ID of the user
  • business_id: ID of the business
  • stars: ratings of the business
  • date: review date
  • text: review from the user
  • useful: number of users who vote a review as usefull
  • funny: number of users who vote a review as funny
  • cool: number of users who vote a review as cool

Summary of Main Tasks¶

Data Input and Filter¶

  • Convert one 8.65GB json file to five json files.
  • Filter out 'Las Vegas', 'Restaurants' data and columns needed, write into seperate CSV files.

Data Cleaning¶

Data cleaning is covered through the whole report, we use:

  • Missing data: Replace all the NaN values by 0 to count the elite members of the Yelp.
  • Remove space at the beginning and end of check-in time.
  • Indexing and reindexing.
  • Renaming axis indexes.
  • Binning: Create bins for restaurant scores, counts, etc.
  • Computing dummy variables for restaurant type.
  • Discretization: Convert multi-valued cell into seperated cell, i.e. seperate the time stamp data into Date, Month and Year Columns.
  • Manipulate time stamp to corresponding weekday.

Data Manipulation¶

  • Slicing: slice top 50 types of the category for Businesses analysis categorically.
  • Arithmetic operations: find all business locations in each year using (business built year <= target year), convert absolute value to relative value for scores of restaurant types.
  • Sorting and ranking: find the Top 10 Las Vegas restaurants in each year.
  • Groupby: using groupby function to group data for individual year, user or business.
  • Group operations: calculate average, count and other statistic attributes for groups.
  • Merge: Merge two dataframes,like business and review, to cross-analyze.
  • Reshaping: Using melt to transform checkin time for each business from wide to long.

Natural Language Processing¶

  • Converting to lower case.
  • Tokenization.
  • Removing stop words.
  • Stemming/Lemmatization.

Visualization¶

  • Interactive bar plot visualization: Visualize the top 10 restaurants and Categories of Cusines for Las Vegas.
  • Interactive stacked bar plot: Visualize the percentage of score from 1-5 for each top type of restaurants.
  • Interactive line plot visualization: Visualize the most popular checkin time in Las Vegas and time distribution of top Las Vegas restaurant types.
  • Interactive subplot visualization: Using bar plot, pie plot, visualize the users based on Review counts per user , average stars per user , Elite Vs. Non-Elite users and Number of Users for the year 2005 to 2018 using the application Yelp.
  • Interactive map visualization: Using mapbox, slider and button to show the increasing of restaurants in Las Vegas from 2011 - 2018. Besides, creating heatmap to show score distribution of Las Vegas restaurants/
  • Word cloud Visualization: using word cloud to show the most common words in Mexican reviews.

# encoding: utf-8

# Define the city we plan to research.
CITY = 'Las Vegas'
BUSINESS_SET = set()
USER_SET = set()

# Define headers for 5 csv files.
BUSINESS_TABLE_COLUMNS = ["business_id", "name", "city", "latitude", "longitude", "stars", "review_count", "categories"]
REVIEW_TABLE_COLUMNS = ["review_id", "user_id", "business_id", "stars", "date", "text", "useful", "funny", "cool"]
USER_TABLE_COLUMNS = ["user_id", "name", "review_count", "yelping_since", "useful", "funny", "cool", "fans", "elite", "average_stars"]
CHECKIN_TABLE_COLUMNS = ["business_id", "date"]
TIP_TABLE_COLUMNS = ["text", "date", "compliment_count", "business_id", "user_id"]

def create_csv(tableName, table_row_names):
    print('Creating', tableName, 'csv file.')  
    preload_necessary_data(tableName)
    rawJsonFile = open(tableName, 'r')
    outputFile = open(tableName + '.csv', 'w')
    writer = csv.writer(outputFile)
    writer.writerow(table_row_names)
    index = 0
    while True:
        line = rawJsonFile.readline().strip()
        if line == None or len(line) == 0:
            break
        current_dict = json.loads(line)
        if csv_write_row(tableName, current_dict, table_row_names, writer):
            index += 1
            if (index % 100000 == 0):
                print ("Handling ", index)
    print(str(index), 'rows in', tableName, 'file.')
    outputFile.close()
    rawJsonFile.close()

# Defind a helper function to write rows in csv file.
def csv_write_row(tableName, current_dict, table_row_names, writer):
    canWrite = False
    if tableName == 'business' and current_dict['city'] == CITY:
        categories = current_dict['categories']
        if categories != None and ('food' in categories or 'restaurant' in categories or 'Food' in categories or "Restaurants" in categories):
            canWrite = True
    elif tableName == 'review':
        if current_dict['business_id'] in BUSINESS_SET:
            canWrite = True
    elif tableName == 'user' and current_dict['user_id'] in USER_SET:
        canWrite = True
    elif tableName == 'checkin' and current_dict['business_id'] in BUSINESS_SET:
        canWrite = True
    elif tableName == 'tip' and current_dict['business_id'] in BUSINESS_SET:
        canWrite = True
    if canWrite:
        currentRowInList = list()
        for item in table_row_names:
            tempValue = current_dict[item]
            currentRowInList.append(tempValue)
        writer.writerow(currentRowInList)
    return canWrite

# Check whether to load businessid and userid set.
def preload_necessary_data(tableName):
    business_required = ["review", "checkin", "tip"]
    user_required = ["user"]
    if tableName in business_required and len(BUSINESS_SET) == 0:
        loading_business()
    elif tableName in user_required and len(USER_SET) == 0:
        loading_user()

# Add businessid, userid to corresponding set.
def loading_business():
    fileHandler = open ("business.csv", "r")
    csv_f = csv.reader(fileHandler)
    for row in csv_f:
        business_id = row[0]
        BUSINESS_SET.add(business_id)
    return BUSINESS_SET

def loading_user():
    fileHandler = open ("review.csv", "r")
    csv_f = csv.reader(fileHandler)
    for row in csv_f:
        USER_SET.add(row[1])
    return USER_SET

# Define a function to convert time stamp in a given check-in time dataframe
# to date, time, year, month, day, weekday.

def get_checkinTime_df(checkinTime):
    checkinTime = pd.DataFrame(checkinTime)
    checkinTime = checkinTime[0].str.split(' ', expand=True)
    checkinTime = checkinTime.reset_index().drop(['level_0','level_1'],axis=1)
    checkinTime.columns = ['Date', 'Time']
    date = checkinTime['Date'].str.split('-', expand=True)
    checkinTime['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(checkinTime['Date'])
    checkinTime = pd.concat((checkinTime, date), axis=1)
    checkinTime.columns = ['Date','Time','Year','Month','Day']
    checkinTime['weekDay'] = checkinTime['Date'].dt.day_name()
    return checkinTime

Analysis 1. Figure Elite users Proportion

The Yelp Elite Squad is our way of recognizing people who are active in the Yelp community and role models on and off the Yelp site. Elite-worthiness is based on a number of things, including well-written reviews, high quality photos, a detailed personal profile, and a history of playing well with others.
As we can see that 7.9% (38802) of the users are Elite members which means rest of the users are casual users who just use Yelp to get to know the place before they visit them and then maybe write a review.

Analysis 2. Number of Reviews by Each User

This is the number of reviews given by each users in an average user lifetime at Yelp till 2018. We have binned the users in different ranges to get the rough idea as there is maximum of 13708 reviews written by a user and this can become one of possible outlier while in-depth analysis. So binning is a great method to get rid of these outliers to get actual analysis.
Almost 40.5% of the users review between 0-5 , which shows mostly people use the app to get to know a place before they can visit.

Analysis 3. Number of Users between 2005-2018

This graph helps us to understand the trend of user base as we can see from 2005 to 2014 there is constant increase in the number of users using Yelp. But after 2015 there starts the downfall of the Yelp as Google, Apple Siri and other competitors enter the market making it difficult for Yelp to increase their customer base.

Analysis 4. Average Stars by Each User

This graph shows us the average stars given by a user in his entire reviews of Yelp Lifecycle. Suppose your are a Yelp User who has just given 5 reviews and all of them are 4 stars. So your Average review till date is 4 stars. We have binned stars in ranges as this is a continuous measure and plotting individual values can lead to infinity. We can see that people are pretty generous for restaurants at Vegas. I mean 45.3 % of them got 4-5 stars. So there can be two reasons for this

  • Either people are drunk and gave the reviews
  • Or Restaurants are really good at Vegas which is why it is one of busiest Nite city of United States.

After preliminary analysis based on one dataset and simple dimension, we decide to merge two dataset and with more dimensions to get more insights.

# Define a function to find out top 10 restaurants for a given year.
def MostVistRestaurant(year):
    year_df = yearGroup.get_group(year).sort_values(by='check-in times',ascending=False)
    year_top10 = year_df[:10].merge(businessWithBuiltDate, left_on = 'business_id', right_on = 'business_id')
    year_top10 = year_top10[['business_id','name_x','check-in times','latitude','longtitude','stars','categories']]
    simple_top10 = year_top10[['name_x','check-in times']]
    simple_top10.columns=[str(year)+'Top10', str(year)+'times']
    return simple_top10

# Tokenizing reviews of Italian restaurants for NLP 

tkn_italian = []

for i in range(len(ls_italian)):
    
    # processing each review
    text_it = ls_italian[i]
    
    # converting each review sentence to tokens
    tokens_it = [w for w in word_tokenize(text_it.lower()) if w.isalpha()]
    
    # removing the stopwords from the tokens_it
    no_stops_it = [t for t in tokens_it if t not in stopwords.words('english')]
    
    # Stemming each word in no_stops_it
    ps_it = PorterStemmer()
    stem_words_it = [ps_it.stem(word) for word in no_stops_it]
    
    # Lemmatizing each word in stemmed words
    word_lemmatizer_it = WordNetLemmatizer()
    lemmatized_it = [word_lemmatizer_it.lemmatize(t) for t in stem_words_it]
    
    # creating a list of all the words in the review
    tkn_italian.append(lemmatized_it)

4. Major Findings¶

  • We find the most popular types of restaurants in Las Vegas. Top 10 types by category are Nightlife, Fast Food, Bars, Coffee & Tea, Sandwiches, Pizza, Burgers, Breakfast & Brunch, Specialty Food, Desserts. Top 10 types by region are American (Traditional), Mexican, American (New), Chinese, Italian, Japanese, Thai, Mediterranean, Hawaiian, Korean.
  • Las Vegas never let people hungry, even in the midnight. The restaurant check-in peak is 2 am. All types of restaurant, even Japanese food and coffee and tea share the same pattern as the total restaurants.
  • The total number of Yelp users increased from 2005 to 2014. However, after 2015 there starts the downfall of the Yelp as Google, Apple Siri and other competitors enter the market making it difficult for Yelp to attract their customer leaving a review.
  • For Yelp users in Las Vegas, we find less than 10% are elite users for Yelp, 40% of them write less than 5 reviews. People are not so passionate to write reviews for Las Vegas.
  • There is a high proportion of restaurants over 4 stars. One reason is that people in Las Vegas are generous to Las Vegas restaurants, another explanation is restaurants are really good here, which also makes sense to a tourist city as Las Vegas. Among all the types, NightLife and Japanese are exceptionally good in Las Vegas.
  • A large volume of good restaurants and also Nightlife restaurant are on the center street. That's the best place to meet a restaurant you may like without doing any research.
  • When talked about Italian food and Mexican food, 'good' is one the most frequent used word people use. Italian food enjoyed a higher percentage of good reviews over Mexican food.

Why our results are meaningful?¶

  • For Yelp, we detect a decrease in user base from 2015 and a lack of motivation to write reviews, which is an important signal for Yelp to put more effort into attracting new users and encouraging users interaction.
  • For business owners, we provide insights in restaurants operation time, location and competitors performance, which could be used to positioning themselves in Las Vegas restaurant market.
  • For residents and visitors, we give suggestions on popular restaurant types, top 10 restaurants over the years and geographical distibution of good restaurants, which can be helpful when looking for something to eat in Las Vegas.
